  "text": "A projection of both strain increment vectors on the ó 9 1 axis yields the axial strain increment from the onset of heating. As seen in Fig. 15(a) , it is a negative-that is, expansive-strain. Such a situation persists until the effective stress point reaches the yield locus at point 2 on the strain-softening side. As the process is dominated by the thermal water expansion strain, the only admissible effective stress increment at q ¼ const. at point 2 is towards the interior of the yield locus (e.g. [CITATION_1] . The ensuing strain rate increment at a generic point 3 relative to 2 now consists of a similar˜å t to that at point 1, an opposite˜å e , and an additional thermoplastic strain ratẽ å p normal to the yield locus. The axial components of the two last (and dominant) strain increments are now compressive, as is the axial strain component. The described process ends when it crosses the critical state line, and as for q ¼ const. it becomes inadmissible from the plasticity point of view, implying failure [CITATION_2] . Clearly, there is no 'characteristic temperature at failure', as it depends strongly on the entire history of all the variables involved. The distance between point 2 and the critical line determines the drop in the pore pressure, which occurs despite the continuously increasing temperature. Physically, this is the result of a significant plastic dilatancy starting from point 2, creating pore space to accommodate further water expansion (Fig. 15(a) ).",
